The plug in interfaces, container runtime, network, and storage.

Kubernetes is deliberately small at the core. Three big plug in points let it talk to whatever runtime, network, and storage you happen to have.

The first is the container runtime interface. It is a gee-are-pee-see ay-pee-eye the kube-let speaks to a local runtime. It has two services, one for creating pods and containers and managing their lifecycle, and one for pulling and listing images. The kube-let does not know whether container-d or cri-oh is on the other end of the socket. It just calls the interface. There is one runtime implementation per node.

The second is the container network interface. It is a small specification, not gee-are-pee-see, for setting up a container's network namespace. When the kube-let creates a pod's network namespace, it invokes the configured network plugin, which allocates a pod eye-pee from the node's pool, programs routing so the pod can reach other pods, services, and the internet, and hands the eye-pee back for the kube-let to record. Common plugins include ka-lee-ko, silly-um, and flannel. They differ in how they encapsulate traffic, how they implement network policy, and their performance, with the ee-bee-pee-eff based ones able to skip eye-pee-tables entirely. The simple cluster, kind, ships with its own plugin called kind net.

The third is the container storage interface, which we covered in the storage notebook. It is how kubernetes talks to any storage backend through a standard driver.

The pattern across all three is identical. Kubernetes defines a contract, and each vendor ships a plugin that obeys it. That is exactly why kubernetes runs the same way on a laptop, in a data centre, and across every cloud.
